Mike:
1) Anaconda is python (for programming), git is version control software.  One does not require the other.  They are separate programs. When you type `$ git` at your terminal you are running git.
2) Just because you uninstalled git doesn't mean that all the repos you previously cloned to your machine disappear.  So you uninstalled and reinstalled git, but the `python-fundamentals` repo that you previously cloned from your fork still exists on your computer.
3) Git error messages are usually very clear.  In this case it told you `python-fundamentals` already exists.  So that means that your previously cloned repo is still there and git isn't going to let you copy over it.
4) That said, you should find your existing `python-fundamentals` folder, cd into it, and then type `git remote -v`.  It should show you the urls associated with your remote origin.  If those say `zipfian` instead of your github name then you cloned zipfians repo, not your forked version on Github, and you will not have permission to `git push` to the zipfian repo.
